E-Waste: A Growing Problem
E-waste, or electronic waste, is a growing global concern. It refers to discarded electronic devices such as computers, smartphones, televisions, and appliances. While these devices contain valuable materials, they also contain harmful substances like lead, mercury, and cadmium.
Why is E-waste a problem?
•	Environmental Harm: Improper disposal of e-waste can pollute soil and water, release harmful gases into the atmosphere, and harm wildlife.
•	Health Risks: Exposure to toxic chemicals in e-waste can cause serious health problems.
•	Resource Depletion: E-waste often ends up in landfills, wasting valuable resources that could be recycled.
What can you do?
•	Reduce: Repair devices when possible, buy durable electronics, and minimize packaging.
•	Reuse: Donate or sell used electronics, and find creative ways to repurpose old devices.
•	Recycle: Find certified e-waste recycling centers in your area.
Remember: E-waste is a serious issue. By making conscious choices and properly disposing of electronic devices, we can reduce our impact on the environment and protect our health.
